history – like those of Stephen Hobhouse, Dame Kathleen Lonsdale, Ian Hamilton, Alfred Hassler, and Donald Wetzel – come alive, detailing the impact of prison life and offering unique perspectives on wartime government policies of conscription and imprisonment. Sometimes intensely moving, and often inspiring, these memoirs show that in some cases, individual conscientious objectors – many well-educated and politically aware – sought to reform the penal system from within either by publicizing its dysfunction or through further resistance to authority. The collection is an essential contribution to our understanding of criminology and the history of pacifism, and represents a valuable addition to prison literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aConscientious objectorsvBiography. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xConscientious objectors. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xConscientious objectors. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xPrisoners and prisons. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConscientious objectors. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPrisoners and prisons. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Criminals & Outlaws.2bisacsh1 aBrock, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGaucher, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262080340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442620803423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442620803/original  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_